<h1>@HI{{you desu}} </h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<dl>
<li> @Vplain{{}} @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{no}} @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}}
<li> <em>demonstrative</em> @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
This sentence pattern is used to convey the speaker's subjective conjecture based on information
the speaker directly perceives. The speaker bases his judgement on first-hand reliable
information, usually visual information.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}} can express either the likelihood of something or the likeness of something to something else.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}} can be used before a noun in the form @EM{{@HI{{youna}}}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{now^day^rice*field^in}}san'no@EM{{youna}}@KJ{{person}}wo@KJ{{see}}mashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I saw a man who looked like Mr. tanaka.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}} can be used before a verb in the form @EM{{@HI{{youni}}}}.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KT{{sumisu}}sanha@KJ{{day^book^person}}no@EM{{youni}}@KJ{{day^book^word}}wo@KJ{{tale}}masu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Mr. Smith speaks Japanese like a Japanese person.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{matter^happenstance}}no@EM{{you desu}} ne. @KT{{patoka-}}to
    @KJ{{salvation^hurry^car}}ga @KJ{{come}}te imasuyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    It looks like there has been an accident. A patrol car and ambulance are there.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{sekimo @KJ{{exit}}rushi, @KJ{{head}}mo @KJ{{pain}}i. doumo kaze wo hita@EM{{you desu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I have a cough and a headache. It looks like I've caught a cold.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The colloquial form of @EM{{@HI{{you desu}}}} is @HI{{mitai}}.
</p>

